{"id": "8352", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=8352", "title": "December 6", "text": "December 6\n\nBULLET::::- 963 – Pope Leo VIII is appointed to the office of Protonotary and begins his papacy as antipope of Rome.\nBULLET::::- 1060 – Béla I is crowned king of Hungary.\nBULLET::::- 1240 – Mongol invasion of Rus': Kiev under Daniel of Galicia and Voivode Dmytro falls to the Mongols under Batu Khan.\nBULLET::::- 1534 – The city of Quito in Ecuador is founded by Spanish settlers led by Sebastián de Belalcázar.\nBULLET::::- 1648 – Colonel Thomas Pride of the New Model Army purges the Long Parliament of MPs sympathetic to King Charles I of England, in order for the King's trial to go ahead; came to be known as \"Pride's Purge\".\nBULLET::::- 1704 – Battle of Chamkaur: During the Mughal-Sikh Wars, an outnumbered Sikh Khalsa defeats a Mughal army.\nBULLET::::- 1745 – Charles Edward Stuart's army begins retreat during the second Jacobite Rising.\nBULLET::::- 1790 – The U.S. Congress moves from New York City to Philadelphia.\nBULLET::::- 1846 – American and Californio forces clash at the Battle of San Pasqual.\nBULLET::::- 1865 – Georgia ratifies 13th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution.\nBULLET::::- 1877 – The first edition of \"The Washington Post\" is published.\nBULLET::::- 1884 – The Washington Monument in Washington, D.C., is completed.\nBULLET::::- 1897 – London becomes the world's first city to host licensed taxicabs.\nBULLET::::- 1904 – Theodore Roosevelt articulated his \"Corollary\" to the Monroe Doctrine, stating that the U.S. would intervene in the Western Hemisphere should Latin American governments prove incapable or unstable.\nBULLET::::- 1907 – A coal mine explosion at Monongah, West Virginia, kills 362 workers.\nBULLET::::- 1912 – The Nefertiti Bust is discovered.\nBULLET::::- 1916 – World War I: The Central Powers capture Bucharest.\nBULLET::::- 1917 – Finland declares independence from Soviet Russia.\nBULLET::::- 1917 – Halifax Explosion: A munitions explosion near Halifax, Nova Scotia kills more than 1,900 people in the largest artificial explosion up to that time.\nBULLET::::- 1917 – World War I: is the first American destroyer to be sunk by enemy action when it is torpedoed by German submarine .\nBULLET::::- 1921 – The Anglo-Irish Treaty is signed in London by British and Irish representatives.\nBULLET::::- 1922 – One year to the day after the signing of the Anglo-Irish Treaty, the Irish Free State comes into existence.\nBULLET::::- 1928 – The government of Colombia sends military forces to suppress a month-long strike by United Fruit Company workers, resulting in an unknown number of deaths.\nBULLET::::- 1933 – U.S. federal judge John M. Woolsey rules that James Joyce's novel \"Ulysses\" is not obscene.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: The United Kingdom and Canada declare war on Finland in support of the Soviet Union during the Continuation War. Camp X opens in Canada to begin training Allied Secret Agents for the War.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II in villages Stary Ciepielów and Rekówka German Genarmerie massacred 31 Poles for helping the Jews. Also, two Jewish refugees were murdered.\nBULLET::::- 1947 – The Everglades National Park in Florida is dedicated.\nBULLET::::- 1953 – Vladimir Nabokov completes his controversial novel \"Lolita\".\nBULLET::::- 1956 – A violent water polo match between Hungary and the USSR takes place during the 1956 Summer Olympics in Melbourne, against the backdrop of the Hungarian Revolution of 1956.\nBULLET::::- 1957 – Project Vanguard: A launchpad explosion of Vanguard TV3 thwarts the first United States attempt to launch a satellite into Earth orbit.\nBULLET::::- 1967 – Adrian Kantrowitz performs the first human heart transplant in the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1969 – Altamont Free Concert: At a free concert performed by the Rolling Stones, eighteen-year old Meredith Hunter is stabbed to death by Hells Angels security guards.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – Pakistan severs diplomatic relations with India, initiating the Indo-Pakistani War of 1971.\nBULLET::::- 1973 – The Twenty-fifth Amendment: The United States House of Representatives votes 387–35 to confirm Gerald Ford as Vice President of the United States. (On November 27, the Senate confirmed him 92–3.)\nBULLET::::- 1975 – The Troubles: Fleeing from the police, a Provisional IRA unit takes a British couple hostage in their flat on Balcombe Street, London, beginning a six-day siege.\nBULLET::::- 1977 – South Africa grants independence to Bophuthatswana, although it is not recognized by any other country.\nBULLET::::- 1978 – Spain ratifies the Spanish Constitution of 1978 in a referendum.\nBULLET::::- 1982 – The Troubles: The Irish National Liberation Army bombs a pub frequented by British soldiers in Ballykelly, Northern Ireland, killing eleven soldiers and six civilians.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – The École Polytechnique massacre (or Montreal Massacre): Marc Lépine, an anti-feminist gunman, murders 14 young women at the École Polytechnique in Montreal.\nBULLET::::- 1991 – Yugoslav Wars: In Croatia, forces of the Serb-dominated Yugoslav People's Army (JNA) bombard Dubrovnik after laying siege to the city for seven months.\nBULLET::::- 1992 – The Babri Masjid in Ayodhya, India, is demolished, leading to widespread riots causing the death of over 1,500 people.\nBULLET::::- 1995 – Khabarovsk United Air Group Flight 3949 crashes into the Bo-Dzhausa Mountain, killing 98.\nBULLET::::- 1997 – A Russian Antonov An-124 Ruslan cargo plane crashes into an apartment complex near Irkutsk, Siberia, killing 67.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – in Venezuela, Hugo Chávez is victorious in presidential elections.\nBULLET::::- 1999 – \"A&M Records, Inc. v. Napster, Inc.\": The Recording Industry Association of America sues the peer-to-peer file-sharing service Napster, alleging copyright infringement.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – An Iranian Air Force C-130 military transport aircraft crashes into a ten-floor apartment building in a residential area of Tehran, killing all 94 on board and 12 more on the ground.\nBULLET::::- 2006 – NASA reveals photographs taken by Mars Global Surveyor suggesting the presence of liquid water on Mars.\nBULLET::::- 2015 – 2015 Venezuelan parliamentary election: For the first time in 17 years, the United Socialist Party of Venezuela loses its majority in parliament.\nBULLET::::- 2017 – Donald Trump's administration officially announces the recognition of Jerusalem as the capital of Israel.\n\nBULLET::::- 846 – Hasan al-Askari, Arabian 11th of the Twelve Imams (d. 874)\nBULLET::::- 1285 – Ferdinand IV of Castile (d. 1312)\nBULLET::::- 1421 – Henry VI of England (d. 1471)\nBULLET::::- 1478 – Baldassare Castiglione, Italian courtier, diplomat, and author (d. 1529)\nBULLET::::- 1520 – Barbara Radziwiłł, queen of Poland (d. 1551)\nBULLET::::- 1545 – Janus Dousa, Dutch historian and noble (d. 1604)\nBULLET::::- 1586 – Niccolò Zucchi, Italian astronomer and physicist (d. 1670)\nBULLET::::- 1592 – William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Newcastle (d. 1676)\nBULLET::::- 1608 – George Monck, 1st Duke of Albemarle, English general and politician, Lord Lieutenant of Ireland (d. 1670)\nBULLET::::- 1637 – Edmund Andros, English courtier and politician, 4th Colonial Governor of New York (d. 1714)\nBULLET::::- 1640 – Claude Fleury, French historian and author (d. 1723)\nBULLET::::- 1642 – Johann Christoph Bach, German organist and composer (d. 1703)\nBULLET::::- 1685 – Marie Adélaïde of Savoy (d. 1712)\nBULLET::::- 1721 – Guillaume-Chrétien de Lamoignon de Malesherbes, French minister and politician (d. 1794)\nBULLET::::- 1721 – James Elphinston, Scottish philologist and linguist (d. 1809)\nBULLET::::- 1752 – Gabriel Duvall, American jurist and politician (d. 1844)\nBULLET::::- 1778 – Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac, French physicist and chemist (d. 1850)\nBULLET::::- 1792 – William II of the Netherlands (d. 1849)\nBULLET::::- 1803 – Maria Josepha Amalia of Saxony (d. 1829)\nBULLET::::- 1805 –