{"id": "8354", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=8354", "title": "December 4", "text": "December 4\n\nBULLET::::- 771 – Austrasian king Carloman I dies, leaving his brother Charlemagne king of the now complete Frankish Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 1110 – The Kingdom of Jerusalem captures Sidon.\nBULLET::::- 1259 – Kings Louis IX of France and Henry III of England agree to the Treaty of Paris, in which Henry renounces his claims to French-controlled territory on continental Europe (including Normandy) in exchange for Louis withdrawing his support for English rebels.\nBULLET::::- 1563 – The final session of the Council of Trent is held. (It had opened on December 13, 1545.)\nBULLET::::- 1619 – Thirty-eight colonists arrive at Berkeley Hundred, Virginia. The group's charter proclaims that the day \"be yearly and perpetually kept holy as a day of thanksgiving to Almighty God.\"\nBULLET::::- 1676 – The Danish army under the command of King Christian V engages the Swedish army commanded by the Swedish king Charles XI at the Battle of Lund, to this day it is counted as the bloodiest battle in Scandinavian history and a turning point in the Scanian War.\nBULLET::::- 1745 – Charles Edward Stuart's army reaches Derby, its furthest point during the Second Jacobite Rising.\nBULLET::::- 1783 – At Fraunces Tavern in New York City, U.S. General George Washington bids farewell to his officers.\nBULLET::::- 1786 – Mission Santa Barbara is dedicated (on the feast day of Saint Barbara).\nBULLET::::- 1791 – The first edition of \"The Observer\", the world's first Sunday newspaper, is published.\nBULLET::::- 1829 – In the face of fierce local opposition, British Governor-General Lord William Bentinck issues a regulation declaring that anyone who abets \"suttee\" in Bengal is guilty of culpable homicide.\nBULLET::::- 1861 – The 109 Electors of the several states of the Confederate States of America unanimously elect Jefferson Davis as President and Alexander H. Stephens as Vice President.\nBULLET::::- 1864 – American Civil War: Sherman's March to the Sea: At Waynesboro, Georgia, forces under Union General Judson Kilpatrick prevent troops led by Confederate General Joseph Wheeler from interfering with Union General William T. Sherman's campaign destroying a wide swath of the South on his march to the Atlantic Ocean from Atlanta.\nBULLET::::- 1865 – North Carolina ratifies 13th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution, followed soon by Georgia, and U.S. slaves were legally free within two weeks.\nBULLET::::- 1867 – Former Minnesota farmer Oliver Hudson Kelley founds the Order of the Patrons of Husbandry (better known today as the Grange).\nBULLET::::- 1872 – The crewless American ship is found by the Canadian brig \"Dei Gratia\". The ship had been abandoned for nine days but was only slightly damaged.\nBULLET::::- 1875 – Notorious New York City politician Boss Tweed escapes from prison; he is later recaptured in Spain.\nBULLET::::- 1881 – The first edition of the \"Los Angeles Times\" is published.\nBULLET::::- 1893 – First Matabele War: A patrol of 34 British South Africa Company soldiers is ambushed and annihilated by more than 3,000 Matabele warriors on the Shangani River in Matabeleland.\nBULLET::::- 1906 – Alpha Phi Alpha the first black intercollegiate Greek lettered fraternity was founded at Cornell University in Ithaca, New York.\nBULLET::::- 1909 – In Canadian football, the First Grey Cup game is played. The University of Toronto Varsity Blues defeat the Toronto Parkdale Canoe Club, 26–6.\nBULLET::::- 1909 – The Montreal Canadiens ice hockey club, the oldest surviving professional hockey franchise in the world, is founded as a charter member of the National Hockey Association.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – U.S. President Woodrow Wilson sails for the World War I peace talks in Versailles, becoming the first US president to travel to Europe while in office.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – World War II: is struck by a mine (laid by ) off the Scottish coast and is laid up for repairs until August 1940.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: Carlson's patrol during the Guadalcanal Campaign ends.\nBULLET::::- 1943 – World War II: In Yugoslavia, resistance leader Marshal Josip Broz Tito proclaims a provisional democratic Yugoslav government in-exile.\nBULLET::::- 1943 – World War II: U.S. President Franklin D. Roosevelt closes down the Works Progress Administration, because of the high levels of wartime employment in the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – By a vote of 65–7, the United States Senate approves United States participation in the United Nations. (The UN had been established on October 24, 1945.)\nBULLET::::- 1949 – Sir Duncan George Stewart was fatally stabbed by Rosli Dhobi, a member leader of the Rukun 13, in Sibu, Sarawak, Malaysia during the British crown colony era in that state.\nBULLET::::- 1954 – The first Burger King is opened in Miami, Florida.\nBULLET::::- 1956 – The Million Dollar Quartet (Elvis Presley, Jerry Lee Lewis, Carl Perkins, and Johnny Cash) get together at Sun Studio for the first and last time.\nBULLET::::- 1964 – Free Speech Movement: Police arrest over 800 students at the University of California, Berkeley, following their takeover and sit-in at the administration building in protest of the UC Regents' decision to forbid protests on UC property.\nBULLET::::- 1965 – The Grateful Dead's first concert performance under this new name.\nBULLET::::- 1965 – Launch of Gemini 7 with crew members Frank Borman and Jim Lovell. The Gemini 7 spacecraft was the passive target for the first crewed space rendezvous performed by the crew of Gemini 6A.\nBULLET::::- 1967 – Vietnam War: U.S. and South Vietnamese forces engage Viet Cong troops in the Mekong Delta.\nBULLET::::- 1969 – Black Panther Party members Fred Hampton and Mark Clark are shot and killed during a raid by 14 Chicago police officers.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – The Indian Navy attacks the Pakistan Navy and Karachi.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – The PNS Ghazi, a submarine belonging to the Pakistan Navy, sinks during the course of the Indo-Pakistani Naval War of 1971.\nBULLET::::- 1977 – Jean-Bédel Bokassa, president of the Central African Republic, crowns himself Emperor Bokassa I of the Central African Empire.\nBULLET::::- 1977 – Malaysian Airline System Flight 653 is hijacked and crashes in Tanjong Kupang, Johor, killing 100.\nBULLET::::- 1978 – Following the murder of Mayor George Moscone, Dianne Feinstein becomes San Francisco's first female mayor.\nBULLET::::- 1979 – The Hastie fire in Hull kills three schoolboys and eventually leads police to arrest Bruce George Peter Lee.\nBULLET::::- 1981 – South Africa grants independence to the Ciskei \"homeland\" (not recognized by any government outside South Africa).\nBULLET::::- 1982 – The People's Republic of China adopts its current constitution.\nBULLET::::- 1983 – US Navy aircraft from USS John F. Kennedy and USS Independence attack Syrian Missile sites in Lebanon in response to an F-14 being fired on by an SA-7. One A-6 Intruder and A-7 Corsair are shot down. 1 American pilot was killed, one was rescued and one is captured.\nBULLET::::- 1984 – Sri Lankan Civil War: Sri Lankan Army soldiers kill 107–150 civilians in Mannar.\nBULLET::::- 1991 – Terry A. Anderson is released after seven years in captivity as a hostage in Beirut; he is the last and longest-held American hostage in Lebanon.\nBULLET::::- 1991 – Pan American World Airways ceases its operations after 64 years.\nBULLET::::- 1992 – Somali Civil War: President George H. W. Bush orders 28,000 U.S. troops to Somalia in Northeast Africa.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – The \"Unity Module\", the second module of the International Space Station, is launched.\nBULLET::::- 2005 – Tens of thousands of people in Hong Kong protest for democracy and call on the government to allow universal and equal suffrage.\nBULLET::::- 2006 – Six black youths assault a white teenager in Jena, Louisiana.\nBULLET::::- 2014 – Islamic insurgents kill three state police at a traffic circle before taking an empty school and a \"press house\" in Grozny. Ten state forces die with 28 injured in gun battles ending with ten insurgents killed.\nBULLET::::- 2015 – A firebomb is thrown into a restaurant in the Egyptian capital of Cairo, killing 17 people.\nBULLET::::- 2017 – The Pontiac Silverdome in Pontiac, Michigan is imploded, one day after failing to be imploded.\nBULLET::::- 2017 – The Thomas Fire starts near Santa Paula in California. It eventually becomes the largest wildfire in modern California history (at that time) after burning in Ventura and Santa Barbara Counties.\n\nBULLET::::- AD 34 – Persius, Roman poet (d. 62)\nBULLET::::- 846 – Hasan al-Askari 11th Imam of Twelver Shia Islam (d. 874)\nBULLET::::- 1428 – Bernard VII, Lord of Lippe (d. 1511)\nBULLET::::- 1506 – Thomas Darcy, 1st Baron Darcy of Chiche (d. 1558)\nBULLET::::- 1555 – Heinrich Meibom, German poet and historian (d. 1625)\nBULLET::::- 1575 – Sister Virginia Maria, Italian nun (d. 1650)\nBULLET::::- 1580 – Samuel Argall, English adventurer and naval officer (d. 1626)\nBULLET::::- 1585 – John Cotton, English-American minister and theologian (d. 1652)\nBULLET::::- 1595 – Jean Chapelain, French poet and critic (d. 1674)\nBULLET::::- 1647 – Daniel Eberlin, German soldier and composer (d. 1715)\nBULLET::::- 1660 – André Campra, French composer and conductor (d. 1744)\nBULLET::::- 1667 – Michel Pignolet de Montéclair, French composer and educator (d. 1737)\nBULLET::::- 1670 – John Aislabie, English politician, Chancellor of the Exchequer (d. 1742)\nBULLET::::- 1713 – Gasparo Gozzi, Italian playwright and critic (d. 1786)\nBULLET::::- 1777 – Juliette Récamier, French businesswoman (d. 1849)\nBULLET::::- 1795 – Thomas Carlyle, Scottish-English historian, philosopher, and academic (d. 1881)\nBULLET::::- 1798 – Jules Armand Dufaure, French lawyer and politician, 33rd Prime Minister of France (d. 1881)\nBULLET::::- 1817 – Nikoloz Baratashvili, Georgian poet and author (