{"id": "8356", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=8356", "title": "December 2", "text": "December 2\n\nBULLET::::- 1244 – Pope Innocent IV arrives at Lyon for the First Council of Lyon.\nBULLET::::- 1409 – The University of Leipzig opens.\nBULLET::::- 1697 – St Paul's Cathedral is consecrated in London.\nBULLET::::- 1763 – Dedication of the Touro Synagogue, in Newport, Rhode Island, the first synagogue in what will become the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1766 – Swedish parliament approved the Swedish Freedom of the Press Act and implemented it as a ground law, thus being first in the world with freedom of speech.\nBULLET::::- 1804 – At Notre Dame Cathedral in Paris, Napoleon Bonaparte crowns himself Emperor of the French.\nBULLET::::- 1805 – War of the Third Coalition: Battle of Austerlitz: French troops under Napoleon Bonaparte decisively defeat a joint Russo-Austrian force.\nBULLET::::- 1823 – Monroe Doctrine: In a State of the Union message, U.S. President James Monroe proclaims American neutrality in future European conflicts, and warns European powers not to interfere in the Americas.\nBULLET::::- 1845 – Manifest destiny: In a State of the Union message, U.S. President James K. Polk proposes that the United States should aggressively expand into the West.\nBULLET::::- 1848 – Franz Joseph I becomes Emperor of Austria.\nBULLET::::- 1851 – French President Louis-Napoléon Bonaparte overthrows the Second Republic.\nBULLET::::- 1852 – Louis-Napoléon Bonaparte becomes Emperor of the French as Napoleon III.\nBULLET::::- 1859 – Militant abolitionist leader John Brown is hanged for his October 16 raid on Harpers Ferry, West Virginia.\nBULLET::::- 1865 – Alabama ratifies 13th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution, followed by North Carolina then Georgia, and U.S. slaves were legally free within two weeks\nBULLET::::- 1867 – At Tremont Temple in Boston, British author Charles Dickens gives his first public reading in the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1899 – Philippine–American War: The Battle of Tirad Pass, termed \"The Filipino Thermopylae\", is fought.\nBULLET::::- 1908 – Puyi becomes Emperor of China at the age of two.\nBULLET::::- 1917 – World War I: Russia and the Central Powers sign an armistice at Brest-Litovsk, and peace talks leading to the Treaty of Brest-Litovsk begin.\nBULLET::::- 1927 – Following 19 years of Ford Model T production, the Ford Motor Company unveils the Ford Model A as its new automobile.\nBULLET::::- 1930 – Great Depression: In a State of the Union message, U.S. President Herbert Hoover proposes a $150 million () public works program to help generate jobs and stimulate the economy.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – New York City's LaGuardia Airport opens.\nBULLET::::- 1942 – World War II: During the Manhattan Project, a team led by Enrico Fermi initiates the first artificial self-sustaining nuclear chain reaction.\nBULLET::::- 1943 – World War II: A Luftwaffe bombing raid on the harbour of Bari, Italy, sinks numerous cargo and transport ships, including the American , which is carrying a stockpile of World War I-era mustard gas.\nBULLET::::- 1947 – Jerusalem Riots of 1947: Riots break out in Jerusalem in response to the United Nations Partition Plan for Palestine.\nBULLET::::- 1949 – Convention for the Suppression of the Traffic in Persons and of the Exploitation of the Prostitution of Others is adopted.\nBULLET::::- 1950 – Korean War: Battle of the Ch'ongch'on River ended, with decisive Chinese victory, UN forces were completely expelled from North Korea.\nBULLET::::- 1954 – Cold War: The United States Senate votes 65 to 22 to censure Joseph McCarthy for \"conduct that tends to bring the Senate into dishonor and disrepute\".\nBULLET::::- 1954 – The Sino-American Mutual Defense Treaty, between the United States and Taiwan, is signed in Washington, D.C.\nBULLET::::- 1956 – The \"Granma\" reaches the shores of Cuba's Oriente Province. Fidel Castro, Che Guevara and 80 other members of the 26th of July Movement disembark to initiate the Cuban Revolution.\nBULLET::::- 1957 – United Nations Security Council Resolution 126 relating to Kashmir conflict is adopted.\nBULLET::::- 1961 – In a nationally broadcast speech, Cuban leader Fidel Castro declares that he is a Marxist–Leninist and that Cuba is going to adopt Communism.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – Vietnam War: After a trip to Vietnam at the request of U.S. President John F. Kennedy, U.S. Senate Majority Leader Mike Mansfield becomes the first American official to comment adversely on the war's progress.\nBULLET::::- 1970 – The United States Environmental Protection Agency begins operations.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – Abu Dhabi, Ajman, Fujairah, Sharjah, Dubai, and Umm al-Quwain form the United Arab Emirates.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – Gough Whitlam is elected Prime Minister of Australia ending 23 years of conservative rule.\nBULLET::::- 1975 – Laotian Civil War: The Pathet Lao seizes the Laotian capital of Vientiane, forces the abdication of King Sisavang Vatthana, and proclaims the Lao People's Democratic Republic.\nBULLET::::- 1976 – Fidel Castro becomes President of Cuba, replacing Osvaldo Dorticós Torrado.\nBULLET::::- 1980 – Salvadoran Civil War: Four American missionaries are raped and murdered by a death squad.\nBULLET::::- 1982 – At the University of Utah, Barney Clark becomes the first person to receive a permanent artificial heart.\nBULLET::::- 1988 – Benazir Bhutto is sworn in as Prime Minister of Pakistan, becoming the first woman to head the government of an Islam-dominated state.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – The Peace Agreement of Hat Yai is signed and ratified by the Malayan Communist Party (MCP) and the governments of Malaysia and Thailand, ending the over two-decade-long communist insurgency in Malaysia.\nBULLET::::- 1991 – Canada and Poland become the first nations to recognize the independence of Ukraine from the Soviet Union.\nBULLET::::- 1993 – Colombian drug lord Pablo Escobar is shot and killed in Medellín.\nBULLET::::- 1993 – Space Shuttle program: STS-61: NASA launches the Space Shuttle \"Endeavour\" on a mission to repair the Hubble Space Telescope.\nBULLET::::- 1999 – The United Kingdom devolves political power in Northern Ireland to the Northern Ireland Executive following the Good Friday Agreement.\nBULLET::::- 2001 – Enron files for Chapter 11 bankruptcy.\nBULLET::::- 2015 – San Bernardino attack: Syed Rizwan Farook and Tashfeen Malik kill 14 people and wound 22 at the Inland Regional Center in San Bernardino, California.\nBULLET::::- 2016 – Thirty-six people die in a fire at a converted Oakland, California, warehouse serving as an artist collective.\n\nBULLET::::- 503 – Emperor Jianwen of Liang, emperor of the Chinese Liang dynasty (d. 551)\nBULLET::::- 1501 – Queen Munjeong, Korean queen (d. 1565)\nBULLET::::- 1578 – Agostino Agazzari, Italian composer and theorist (d. 1641)\nBULLET::::- 1599 – Thomas Bruce, 1st Earl of Elgin, Scottish nobleman (d. 1663)\nBULLET::::- 1629 – William Egon of Fürstenberg, Catholic cardinal (d. 1704)\nBULLET::::- 1694 – William Shirley, English-American lawyer and politician, Governor of the Province of Massachusetts Bay (d. 1771)\nBULLET::::- 1703 – Ferdinand Konščak, Croatian missionary and explorer (d. 1759)\nBULLET::::- 1738 – Richard Montgomery, Irish-American general (d. 1775)\nBULLET::::- 1754 – William Cooper, American judge and politician, founded Cooperstown, New York (d. 1809)\nBULLET::::- 1759 – James Edward Smith, English botanist and mycologist, founded the Linnean Society (d. 1828)\nBULLET::::- 1760 – John Breckinridge, American soldier, lawyer, and politician, 5th United States Attorney General (d. 1806)\nBULLET::::- 1760 – Joseph Graetz, German organist, composer, and educator (d. 1826)\nBULLET::::- 1810 – Henry Yesler, American businessman and politician, 7th Mayor of Seattle (d. 1892)\nBULLET::::- 1811 – Jean-Charles Chapais, Canadian farmer and politician, 1st Canadian Minister of Agriculture (d. 1885)\nBULLET::::- 1817 – Heinrich von Sybel, G